{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17637162","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17637162"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:38:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:38:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17633"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17633","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17633"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.21,0.68,0,0,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10347"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71804"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10347","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10347"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17633"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57293"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10006"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24196"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24207"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24236"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71804","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71804"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe gastric proton pump has an exact mechanism of action.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes this action?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Exchanges one hydrogen ion for two chloride ions","Exchanges one hydrogen ion for one potassium ion","Exchanges two hydrogen ions for one sodium ion","Exchanges two potassium ions for one calcium ion","Exchanges three sodium ions for two potassium ions"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe gastric proton pump (hydrogen-potassium ATPase) \u003Cstrong\u003Eexchanges one hydrogen ion for one potassium ion \u003C/strong\u003Eusing ATP. This active transport mechanism in the apical membrane of parietal cells is essential for creating the acidic environment of the stomach.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExchanges two hydrogen ions for one sodium ion\u003C/strong\u003E - This is not the correct stoichiometry; the pump specifically exchanges potassium, not sodium\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExchanges three sodium ions for two potassium ions\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes the sodium-potassium ATPase, which is found in the basolateral membrane\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExchanges one hydrogen ion for two chloride ions\u003C/strong\u003E - While chloride secretion occurs in parietal cells, it uses different channels\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExchanges two potassium ions for one calcium ion\u003C/strong\u003E - The proton pump does not transport calcium ions\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe hydrogen-potassium ATPase is the primary target of proton pump inhibitor medications used to reduce gastric acid secretion.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Gastric parietal cells use hydrogen-potassium ATPase (proton pump) to secrete hydrogen ions into the stomach lumen.","The proton pump exchanges one hydrogen ion for one potassium ion across the apical membrane using ATP hydrolysis.","This active transport mechanism creates the highly acidic gastric environment with pH around 2."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57293"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17633"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57293","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57293"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-20T15:59:28+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-20T15:59:57+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10347"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71804"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4928"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udca9","name":"Gastrointestinal","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:50:24+10:30"},"relationships